## 5. Monitoring & Health Checks

### 5.1 What Health Checks Are

A health check is an endpoint that answers one question: **"Is this service ready to handle requests?"**

Think of it like a pilot's pre-flight checklist:
- ✅ Engines running? (process alive)
- ✅ Fuel level OK? (disk space)
- ✅ Instruments working? (database reachable)
- ✅ Cabin pressure normal? (memory usage)

If any check fails, the plane doesn't take off — and your load balancer stops sending traffic to that server.

### 5.2 Our Health Check Architecture

```
                    ┌─────────────────────────────┐
                    │ GET /api/health              │
                    │ (HealthController)           │
                    └──────────┬──────────────────┘
                               │
                    ┌──────────▼──────────────────┐
                    │  HealthCheckService          │
                    │  (from @nestjs/terminus)      │
                    │                              │
                    │  Runs all indicators:        │
                    └──┬────┬────┬────┬────────────┘
                       │    │    │    │
          ┌────────────▼┐ ┌─▼──┐ ┌▼──┐ ┌▼────────┐
          │ PrismaHealth│ │Heap│ │RSS│ │  Disk   │
          │ Indicator   │ │    │ │   │ │ Storage │
          │             │ │<256│ │<512│ │  <90%  │
          │ SELECT 1    │ │ MB │ │ MB│ │  used  │
          └─────────────┘ └────┘ └───┘ └─────────┘
```

**Response when healthy** (status 200):
```json
{
  "status": "ok",
  "info": {
    "database": { "status": "up" },
    "memory_heap": { "status": "up" },
    "memory_rss": { "status": "up" },
    "disk": { "status": "up" }
  }
}
```

**Response when unhealthy** (status 503):
```json
{
  "status": "error",
  "error": {
    "database": { "status": "down", "message": "SQLITE_CANTOPEN" }
  }
}
```

### 5.3 Liveness vs Readiness Probes

These concepts come from Kubernetes but apply everywhere:

| Probe | Question | Our Endpoint | What Happens on Failure |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Liveness** | "Is the process alive?" | `GET /api/health/liveness` | Restart the container |
| **Readiness** | "Can it serve traffic?" | `GET /api/health` | Stop sending traffic, don't restart |

**Example scenario**: Your app is running (liveness = OK) but the database is down (readiness = FAIL). Kubernetes will stop routing traffic to this pod but won't restart it — because restarting won't fix a database problem.

### 5.4 The Custom PrismaHealthIndicator

Since Terminus doesn't have built-in Prisma support, we created a custom one ([prisma.health.ts](file:///d:/1_Hoc_Tap/1_1_Dai_Hoc/Tai_lieu_ki_2_nam_3/T2_Kien_truc_phan_mem/Do-an-flashcard/FlashCardBackend/Flash_Learn_BE/src/services/health/prisma.health.ts)):

```typescript
async isHealthy(key: string): Promise<HealthIndicatorResult> {
  await this.prisma.$queryRawUnsafe('SELECT 1');  // Cheapest possible query
  return this.getStatus(key, true);               // { database: { status: "up" } }
}
```

**Why `SELECT 1`?** It's the lightest query possible — it doesn't touch any table, doesn't read any data. It only verifies that the database connection is alive and responsive. Health checks run frequently (every 10-30 seconds), so they must be cheap.

### 5.5 How Metrics Differ From Logs

| Aspect | Logs | Metrics |
|---|---|---|
| **Format** | Text/JSON events | Numerical time-series |
| **Volume** | One per event (can be millions/day) | Aggregated (compact) |
| **Question** | "What happened at 10:03:15?" | "What's the error rate over the last hour?" |
| **Storage** | Log files / Elasticsearch | Prometheus / InfluxDB |
| **Visualization** | Kibana / text search | Grafana dashboards |
| **Cost** | Expensive at scale | Very cheap |

> **Note**: Our implementation includes health checks for monitoring. Prometheus metrics (request duration histograms, error rate counters) can be added later with `@willsoto/nestjs-prometheus` when the system scales beyond a single instance.

---

## 6. Development vs Production Behavior

| Feature | Development | Production |
|---|---|---|
| **Console format** | Colorized, human-readable | Structured JSON |
| **Log level** | `debug` (show everything) | `info` (hide debug noise) |
| **Stack traces** | Shown in console | Written to file only |
| **File logging** | ✅ Active (for testing) | ✅ Active (critical) |
| **Error file retention** | 30 days | 30 days |
| **Combined file retention** | 14 days | 14 days |
| **Health check strictness** | Informational | Determines traffic routing |
| **Performance impact** | Acceptable (more verbose) | Minimal (less verbose) |

**Console output comparison:**

Development:
```
2026-05-14 09:45:58 info [HTTP] GET /api/health 200 - 376b 699ms - Mozilla/5.0... ::1
```
↑ Colored, timestamp formatted for humans, readable at a glance.

Production:
```json
{"context":"HTTP","level":"info","message":"GET /api/health 200 - 376b 699ms","timestamp":"2026-05-14T02:54:42.057Z"}
```
↑ No colors, structured JSON, machine-parsable by Datadog/ELK/CloudWatch.

