## 7. Security & Best Practices

### 7.1 Never Log Sensitive Data

```typescript
// ❌ NEVER DO THIS
this.logger.log(`User login: email=${email}, password=${password}`);
this.logger.log(`Payment processed: card=${creditCardNumber}`);
this.logger.log(`Auth token: ${jwtToken}`);

// ✅ DO THIS INSTEAD
this.logger.log(`User login: email=${email}`);
this.logger.log(`Payment processed: card=****${last4Digits}`);
this.logger.log(`Auth: token validated for user ${userId}`);
```

**What should NEVER appear in logs:**
- Passwords, API keys, JWT tokens
- Credit card numbers, SSNs
- Full email addresses (in GDPR regions)
- Database connection strings with credentials

### 7.2 Log Retention and Compliance

Our rotation settings align with common practices:

| Data Type | Our Retention | GDPR Consideration |
|---|---|---|
| Error logs | 30 days | May contain PII in error messages — review |
| Combined logs | 14 days | Contains IPs and user agents |
| Exception logs | 30 days | May contain request bodies |

### 7.3 The Information Security Principle in Our Filter

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────┐
│           Exception Occurs              │
└────────────────┬────────────────────────┘
                 │
    ┌────────────┴────────────┐
    │                         │
    ▼                         ▼
 INTERNAL LOG              CLIENT RESPONSE
 (full detail)             (sanitized)
                           
 ✅ Stack trace            ❌ No stack trace
 ✅ File paths             ❌ No file paths
 ✅ DB error codes         ❌ No DB details
 ✅ Request body           ❌ No internal state
```

**Why this matters**: If a hacker sends a malformed request and gets back a stack trace showing `at PrismaService.query (/src/services/prisma.service.ts:42)`, they now know:
- You use Prisma (ORM)
- Your file structure
- Potentially your query patterns

Our filter returns only `"Internal server error"` for unexpected errors.

